Note:
Runtime thread-pool API — a fixed-size pool of worker threads draining a
shared FIFO task queue for the Runa runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. It composes three already-complete
lower layers and adds no new locking or scheduling mechanism of its own:

  - WORKERS come from thread_core (which delegates to the per-architecture OS
    thread primitives). Each worker is an OS thread that runs the module-level
    pool_worker_main entry point. Its address is taken with the $name
    function-pointer operator, which the codegen lowers to a RIP-relative
    address computation, exactly as the actor subsystem spawns its threads.
  - MUTUAL EXCLUSION over the shared queue comes from the runtime RuntimeMutex
    (mutex.runa). One RuntimeMutex guards every field of the pool that more
    than one thread touches: the ring buffer, its head/tail/count, the
    shutdown flag and the pending-task counter.
  - CONDITION COORDINATION comes from two runtime RuntimeCondVar objects
    (condition_variable.runa), both paired with the single queue mutex:
      * not_empty — workers block on it while the queue is empty and no
        shutdown has been requested; pool_submit signals it after enqueuing a
        task and pool_shutdown broadcasts it to release every parked worker.
      * drained  — pool_wait_idle blocks on it until every submitted task has
        completed; a worker broadcasts it when it drives the pending counter
        to zero.
    Per the condvar contract, the RuntimeMutex object handle is passed to
    condvar_wait (it extracts the inner sync_core handle at offset 0), and
    every wait is wrapped in a predicate loop so spurious or broadcast wakes
    re-check the shared state before proceeding.

A task is two Integers stored contiguously in the ring buffer: a function
pointer (fn, a $name address) and an opaque argument pointer (arg). A worker
runs a task by invoking call_indirect_1(fn, arg).

The ring buffer is a contiguous array of fixed 16-byte slots. It starts at
POOL_INITIAL_CAPACITY slots and DOUBLES on demand: when pool_submit finds the
ring full it allocates a ring of twice the capacity, copies the live tasks
into it in FIFO order (re-basing head to 0), frees the old ring, and pushes
into the grown ring. The pool therefore never drops or blocks a submission
because of a transient queue-size limit.

Shutdown is clean and lossless: pool_shutdown sets the shutdown flag, wakes
every worker, and joins them. A worker only exits once the queue is fully
drained AND shutdown is set, so every task already submitted is executed
before the pool tears down. Only then are the condition variables, the mutex,
the ring, the worker-id array and the pool object released.

ThreadPool layout (96 bytes):
    offset  0:  mutex       — RuntimeMutex guarding all shared fields
    offset  8:  not_empty   — RuntimeCondVar workers wait on for tasks
    offset 16:  drained     — RuntimeCondVar pool_wait_idle waits on
    offset 24:  ring        — pointer to the task ring buffer
    offset 32:  head        — index of the oldest queued task
    offset 40:  tail        — index where the next task is written
    offset 48:  count       — number of tasks currently in the ring
    offset 56:  capacity    — ring capacity in slots
    offset 64:  shutdown    — 0 running, 1 shutting down
    offset 72:  pending     — submitted tasks not yet completed
    offset 80:  workers     — number of worker threads
    offset 88:  tids        — pointer to the worker thread-id array

Task ring slot layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  fn   — task function pointer
    offset 8:  arg  — task argument pointer
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/thread_core.runa" as Thread
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/condition_variable.runa" as CondVar
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: ThreadPool object layout
Constant POOL_SIZE as Integer is 96
Constant POOL_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant POOL_OFF_NOT_EMPTY as Integer is 8
Constant POOL_OFF_DRAINED as Integer is 16
Constant POOL_OFF_RING as Integer is 24
Constant POOL_OFF_HEAD as Integer is 32
Constant POOL_OFF_TAIL as Integer is 40
Constant POOL_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 48
Constant POOL_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 56
Constant POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN as Integer is 64
Constant POOL_OFF_PENDING as Integer is 72
Constant POOL_OFF_WORKERS as Integer is 80
Constant POOL_OFF_TIDS as Integer is 88

Note: Task ring slot layout
Constant POOL_SLOT_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant POOL_SLOT_OFF_FN as Integer is 0
Constant POOL_SLOT_OFF_ARG as Integer is 8

Note: Size of a single worker thread-id entry in the tids array
Constant POOL_TID_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note: Initial ring capacity in slots; doubled on demand when the ring fills
Constant POOL_INITIAL_CAPACITY as Integer is 256

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime thread-pool API
Constant POOL_OK as Integer is 0
Constant POOL_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant POOL_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 2

Process called "pool_worker_main" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The per-worker run loop. Every worker thread executes this same body:
    block until work arrives, take exactly one task off the head of the FIFO
    ring, run it outside the lock so sibling workers can proceed in parallel,
    then account for its completion. The loop is the only consumer side of the
    queue, so all dequeue bookkeeping lives here under the single queue mutex.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the shared mutex and condvar handles once (they never change for the
    life of the pool). Then loop forever:
      1. Acquire the queue mutex.
      2. Wait on not_empty while the queue is empty and shutdown is not set.
         The wait is wrapped in a predicate loop (should_wait) so a broadcast
         or spurious wake re-evaluates count and shutdown before proceeding,
         and condvar_wait receives the RuntimeMutex object (it extracts the
         inner sync_core handle itself).
      3. If the queue is drained and shutdown is set, release the mutex and
         return — this is the only exit, and it cannot strand queued work
         because it requires count to be zero.
      4. Pop the head slot, advancing head with wraparound and decrementing
         count, then release the mutex.
      5. Run the task via call_indirect_1(fn, arg) with no lock held.
      6. Re-acquire the mutex, decrement pending, and broadcast drained when
         pending reaches zero so pool_wait_idle can return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex acquire/release pair per task plus a second short critical
    section for completion accounting. Idle workers park on the OS futex via
    condvar_wait and consume no CPU. The task itself runs entirely outside the
    lock, so worker parallelism is bounded only by the work, not the queue.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null pool returns immediately. The function pointer invoked is supplied
    by pool_submit's caller; this layer performs the indirect call faithfully
    and does not validate the target, matching call_indirect_1's contract.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX
    Let not_empty be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_NOT_EMPTY
    Let drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_DRAINED

    Loop forever:
        proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

        Note: Block until a task is queued or a shutdown has been requested.
        Let should_wait be 1
        While should_wait is equal to 1:
            Let queued be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT
            Let shutting_down be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN
            If queued is not equal to 0:
                Set should_wait to 0
            Otherwise:
                If shutting_down is not equal to 0:
                    Set should_wait to 0
                Otherwise:
                    proc condvar_wait from CondVar with not_empty, mtx
                End If
            End If
        End While

        Note: Exit only once the queue is fully drained and shutdown is set.
        Let count_now be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT
        Let shutdown_now be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN
        If count_now is equal to 0:
            If shutdown_now is not equal to 0:
                proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
                Return 0
            End If
        End If

        Note: Pop one task from the head of the ring (FIFO order).
        Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_HEAD
        Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_CAPACITY
        Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING
        Let slot_offset be head multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
        Let slot_addr be ring plus slot_offset
        Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_FN
        Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with slot_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_ARG

        Let new_head be head plus 1
        If new_head is equal to capacity:
            Set new_head to 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_HEAD, new_head

        Let count_after be count_now minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT, count_after

        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx

        Note: Run the task with no lock held so other workers can proceed.
        proc call_indirect_1 from Call with fn, arg

        Note: Account for completion; wake pool_wait_idle when fully drained.
        proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
        Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING
        Let pending_after be pending minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING, pending_after
        If pending_after is equal to 0:
            proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with drained
        End If
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    End Loop

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "pool_new" takes worker_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a ready-to-use pool. The caller either fixes the worker count or
    passes a non-positive value to let the pool size itself to the hardware's
    concurrency. Construction allocates every owned resource, initializes the
    shared state, and only then spawns the workers so each worker observes a
    fully formed pool from its first instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Resolve the worker count (falling back to thread_hardware_concurrency,
    floored at 1). Allocate the pool object, the initial ring, and the
    worker-id array; create the queue mutex and both condition variables. On
    any failure, unwind exactly the resources already acquired and return 0.
    Initialize all layout fields (empty ring, zero counters, running state),
    then spawn each worker on pool_worker_main with the pool as its argument,
    recording the returned thread id in the tids array.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path: a handful of allocations, one mutex and two condvar creations,
    and N OS thread spawns. Done once per pool. The ring is sized to absorb a
    burst of POOL_INITIAL_CAPACITY submissions before the first grow.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Every allocation and creation is checked; partial failure frees what was
    acquired and returns 0 (NULL), so callers MUST check the result before
    use. No field is published to a worker until the whole pool is initialized.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let workers be worker_count
    If workers is less than or equal to 0:
        Set workers to proc thread_hardware_concurrency from Thread
        If workers is less than 1:
            Set workers to 1
        End If
    End If

    Let pool be proc allocate from Memory with POOL_SIZE
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ring_bytes be POOL_INITIAL_CAPACITY multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
    Let ring be proc allocate from Memory with ring_bytes
    If ring is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tids_bytes be workers multiplied by POOL_TID_SIZE
    Let tids be proc allocate from Memory with tids_bytes
    If tids is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let not_empty be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If not_empty is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let drained be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If drained is equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with not_empty
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Publish a fully formed, empty, running pool before any worker starts.
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_NOT_EMPTY, not_empty
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_DRAINED, drained
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING, ring
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_HEAD, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TAIL, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_CAPACITY, POOL_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_WORKERS, workers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TIDS, tids

    Note: Spawn the workers. The $name operator yields pool_worker_main's
    Note: real entry address, which the codegen lowers to a RIP-relative load.
    Let worker_fn be $pool_worker_main
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than workers:
        Let tid be proc thread_create from Thread with worker_fn, pool
        Let tid_offset be i multiplied by POOL_TID_SIZE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, tid_offset, tid
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return pool
End Process

Process called "pool_submit" takes pool as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Enqueue one task for asynchronous execution by a worker. Submission never
    fails because of a full queue: the ring grows on demand, so the only hard
    failure is exhausting memory while growing.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the queue mutex, if the ring is full, double it: allocate a new ring,
    copy the live tasks into it in FIFO order (oldest at index 0), free the old
    ring, and re-base head to 0 and tail to the live count. Then write (fn,arg)
    into the tail slot, advance tail with wraparound, increment both the queued
    count and the pending count, signal not_empty to release one parked worker,
    and release the mutex.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path (no grow): one mutex acquire/release, two field stores for the
    slot, four counter updates, and one condvar_signal (a single futex wake).
    Grow path is amortized O(1): it copies count entries but only when the ring
    has doubled, so total copy work is linear in tasks submitted.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns POOL_ERR_NULL. A failed grow allocation releases the lock
    and returns POOL_ERR_ALLOC without mutating the queue, leaving the pool
    fully usable. The lock is always released on every return path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX
    Let not_empty be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_NOT_EMPTY
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_CAPACITY

    If count is equal to capacity:
        Note: Ring is full — grow it to double capacity, copying in FIFO order.
        Let old_ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING
        Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_HEAD
        Let new_capacity be capacity multiplied by 2
        Let new_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
        Let new_ring be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
        If new_ring is equal to 0:
            proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
            Return POOL_ERR_ALLOC
        End If

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than count:
            Let src_index be head plus j
            Set src_index to src_index modulo by capacity
            Let src_offset be src_index multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
            Let src_addr be old_ring plus src_offset
            Let copied_fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_FN
            Let copied_arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with src_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_ARG
            Let dst_offset be j multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
            Let dst_addr be new_ring plus dst_offset
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_FN, copied_fn
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dst_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_ARG, copied_arg
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Memory with old_ring
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING, new_ring
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_HEAD, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TAIL, count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_CAPACITY, new_capacity
        Set capacity to new_capacity
    End If

    Note: Push (fn, arg) into the tail slot and advance tail with wraparound.
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TAIL
    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING
    Let push_offset be tail multiplied by POOL_SLOT_SIZE
    Let push_addr be ring plus push_offset
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with push_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_FN, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with push_addr, POOL_SLOT_OFF_ARG, arg

    Let new_tail be tail plus 1
    If new_tail is equal to capacity:
        Set new_tail to 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TAIL, new_tail

    Let count_inc be count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_COUNT, count_inc

    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING
    Let pending_inc be pending plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING, pending_inc

    proc condvar_signal from CondVar with not_empty
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return POOL_OK
End Process

Process called "pool_pending" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many submitted tasks have not yet finished — those still queued
    plus those currently executing in a worker. Read under the lock so the
    count is a coherent snapshot rather than a torn read.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the queue mutex, read the pending counter, release, and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex acquire/release and a single field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns POOL_ERR_NULL. Advisory: the count may change the instant
    the lock is released.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return pending
End Process

Process called "pool_wait_idle" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the calling thread until every submitted task has completed. This is
    the join point for callers that fan work out to the pool and must observe
    all results before proceeding.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the queue mutex and wait on the drained condition variable while
    the pending counter is above zero, re-reading pending after each wake (a
    worker broadcasts drained exactly when it drives pending to zero). The wait
    receives the RuntimeMutex object, which condvar_wait atomically releases and
    re-acquires. Release the mutex once pending has reached zero.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Parks on the OS futex via condvar_wait with no busy-waiting. Returns
    immediately when no tasks are pending.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns POOL_ERR_NULL. On return the lock is released and all
    work submitted before the call has finished executing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX
    Let drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_DRAINED
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING
    While pending is greater than 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with drained, mtx
        Set pending to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_PENDING
    End While

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return POOL_OK
End Process

Process called "pool_worker_count" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report the number of worker threads the pool was constructed with, for
    diagnostics and for callers that size their work distribution to the pool.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the immutable worker-count field. It is fixed at construction and
    never mutated thereafter, so no lock is required.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    A single field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns POOL_ERR_NULL. Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_WORKERS
End Process

Process called "pool_shutdown" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Drain, stop, and destroy the pool. Every task already submitted runs to
    completion before any worker exits, so shutdown is lossless. After the
    workers have joined, every owned resource is released.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the queue mutex, set the shutdown flag and broadcast not_empty so
    every parked worker wakes, observes shutdown, and either drains a remaining
    task or exits once the queue is empty. Release the mutex, then join every
    worker thread (thread_join tolerates a zero id, so a failed spawn is
    skipped safely). With all workers stopped and no thread left touching the
    pool, destroy both condition variables and the mutex, then deallocate the
    ring, the worker-id array, and the pool object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path: one broadcast, N thread joins, two condvar destroys, one mutex
    destroy, and three deallocations. Blocks until the queue is fully drained.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns POOL_ERR_NULL. After this call the pool pointer is
    invalid and MUST NOT be reused. Calling it concurrently with itself on the
    same pool is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return POOL_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_MUTEX
    Let not_empty be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_NOT_EMPTY
    Let drained be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_DRAINED

    Note: Request shutdown and release every worker parked on not_empty.
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
    proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with not_empty
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx

    Note: Join every worker so no thread touches the pool after teardown.
    Let workers be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_WORKERS
    Let tids be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_TIDS
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than workers:
        Let tid_offset be i multiplied by POOL_TID_SIZE
        Let tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, tid_offset
        proc thread_join from Thread with tid
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: All workers stopped — release every owned resource.
    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, POOL_OFF_RING
    proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with not_empty
    proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with drained
    proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
    proc deallocate from Memory with ring
    proc deallocate from Memory with tids
    proc deallocate from Memory with pool
    Return POOL_OK
End Process
